                {
                  "key": "response",
                  "value": {
                    "stringValue": "## Prerequisites\n\nPython 3.14 (already on this machine) with `pytest` installed for tests — no other dependencies (stdlib only). Run all commands from `C:\\proj\\Oltp-Extracter`.\n\n## 1. Run the unit tests first (fast sanity check)\n\n```powershell\npython -m pytest tests/ -v\n```\nExpect 18 passed. If this fails, don't bother running the CLI — fix the failing test first.\n\n## 2. Dry-run against real data (no files written)\n\n```powershell\npython -m extractor --input received --output extracted --dry-run\n```\nPrints one tab-separated line per would-be record: `session_id  request_id  model  cost  jira_key  skill  agent`. Use this to eyeball correctness before trusting file output.\n\n## 3. Real run (writes files)\n\n```powershell\npython -m extractor --input received --output extracted\n```\nOutput: `extracted\\<session_id>\\<timestamp>_<request_id>.json` — one file per `api_request` event. State is persisted to `.state\\<session_id>.json` so subsequent runs (e.g. once the collector drops new files over time) resume correctly.\n\nOptional flags: `--state-dir <path>` (default `.state`) if you want to point at a different state location, e.g. for a clean test run.\n\n## How to validate\n\n**a) Record count matches source data** — every `api_request` event should produce exactly one file:\n```powershell\ngrep -o '\"api_request\"' received/logs/*.json | wc -l   # or: (Select-String -Path received\\logs\\*.json -Pattern '\"api_request\"').Count\nfind extracted -type f | wc -l\n```\nBoth should match (27 in the current sample set).\n\n**b) Spot-check a record's schema** — open any file under `extracted\\<session_id>\\` and confirm the 12 fields plus `_meta` are populated as expected (`Model`, `Cost USD` non-null; `JIRA Key` present if any prompt in that session ever mentioned one; `Skills` only non-null for the specific turn that invoked a skill; `Agent` currently always `null` — unverified, expected).\n\n**c) JIRA carry-forward** — grep all output files for `JIRA Key` and confirm it's consistent with what was typed in `user_prompt` events for that session (never resets until a new key appears):\n```powershell\ngrep -h \"JIRA Key\" extracted/*/*.json | sort -u\n```\n\n**d) Skill scoping** — confirm `\"Skills\"` is non-null only on records whose `_meta.prompt_id` matches a `skill_activated` event's `prompt_id`, and `null` everywhere else in that session.\n\n**e) Idempotency** — run the CLI a second time over the same input; it should report `Wrote 0 record(s), skipped N already-written` and the file count under `extracted\\` should be unchanged:\n```powershell\npython -m extractor --input received --output extracted\nfind extracted -type f | wc -l   # same number as before\n```\n\nIf you later get real files dropped into `received\\logs\\` (not just this sample set), just re-run the same command — it only processes what's there and skips anything already written by `request_id`, so it's safe to run repeatedly or on a schedule."
